Competition


Overview

What is the U.S. Department of Energy Solar Decathlon?

The Solar Decathlon is a competition that challenges collegiate teams to design, build, and operate solar-powered houses that are cost-effective, energy-efficient, and attractive. Each team spends two years creating a house that is scored according to 10 different competitions, each worth 100 points.  The winner is the team that best blends affordability, consumer appeal, and design excellence with optimal energy production and maximum efficiency. Team Tennessee is one of the seventeen teams that will be competing in Irvine, California in the fall of 2015.

Learn more


the events

what it takes to win

1

Architecture

Our home needs an innovative design approach that is well integrated and holistic in order to compete with the futuristic designs of our competitors. Our design needs to be comprehensive among its plumbing, electrical, mechanical, structural and landscaping sections. A jury of professionals will judge our design, material selection, finished structure and creativity within this contest.

 

2

Market Appeal

In this competition, the Market Appeal jury evaluates the house design to the targeted cliental. A new rule for 2015 requires the homes to be designed as primary residencies for up to one year. Therefore, designs must be livable, buildable and appealing enough to sell on a housing market. In the case of Harmony House, we are marketing lower income families in highly populated areas through Habitat for Humanity. Our hope is to design an efficient and affordable house that will save money on energy bills for our families.

 

3

Engineering
To receive the most points from the jury of Engineers, our home must use high-technology efficient systems which are functional and reliable for years to come. The competition favors unique designs that are both comfortable and high performing. Our house also must be well documented, which means that our planning and designs accurately reflect the final project in Irvine.

4

Communications
To win this juried contest, Team Tennessee needs to  effectively share our home, experiences and project with the rest of the world. This requires a communication platform that is comprehensive, consistent and enjoyable. Online audiences, audiovisual presentations and house tours are all included within the Communications contest.

5

Affordability
To receive a full 100 point score in this competition, a professional estimator must value our home at under $250,000. Since Harmony House is designed for the affordable housing market, we fully anticipate a perfect score.

6

Comfort Zone
To win all 100 points in this competition, our home's temperature must stay between 71°F and 76°F, and have relative humidity of under 60% for the span of the competition.

7

Appliances
This contest measures whether or not our home's appliances can perform the tasks an average family would need, including refrigeration and freezing, washing and drying laundry, cooking, and doing the dishes.

8

Home Life
Harmony House must demonstrate the ability to sustain typical household activities, like leaving lights on, having friends over for dinner, holding a movie night, and running hot water for showers.

9

Commuting
Transportation, a necessary transaction in families, is included in the competition to ensure 100% efficiency of the home. Harmony House must fuel an electric car and drive it over 25 miles in 2 hours at 8 specified times during the week of the competition.

10

Energy Balance
To receive the full 100 points for this competition, our home must create as much or more energy than it uses, and consume less than 175 kWh of energy over the course of the full competition.
